The Rev War Minute  17 March 1776, Boston, Massachusetts. An 11-month siege ended when General William Howe loaded 9,000 British troops and 1,000 Loyalists onto 125 ships bound for Halifax, Nova Scotia. General Washington agreed to a cease-fire during the departure in exchange for sparing the city from destruction. However, some homes and shops were plundered. The British withdrawal boosted American morale and turned New England into a sideshow for the remainder of the war. General Howe, for his part, refitted in Halifax while planning to sail south with his fleet, shifting the focus of the action to the Middle Atlantic region where the navy could assume a more prominent role and more Loyalists awaited to rally to the crown. What seemed impossible a year ago was now a reality; the British had never returned to Boston. With their departure came an end to large-scale military operations in New England. This area, which had done so much to inspire the American Revolution, would now observe events further south, first in the mid-Atlantic states and then in the Carolinas. #RevWar #History #AmRev

Have we been conned? Serious question. Afterall Russia spent a huge amount of resources to construct multiple defensive lines but the evidence such as it is may be showing a different picture.  Please if you enjoy my work help my reach with a boost and a RT and I will work hard to earn it.  Long Ass Tweet Warning!  Pre-Counter Offensive it looked like the Russian's MLR was set back from the FLOC likely to reduce exposure to artillery, reduce enemy counter-battery options, drones, patrols and other ISR assets before the battle kicked off. Sensible thing to do, plus importantly it let Russia choose the terrain the main fight would be on.  The Russians had months to site, build and prepare a series of defensive works to receive and absorb any Ukrainian attack using troops who were mostly rested and who had a chance to learn soldier skills and the terrain they would fight on.  So why fight so hard forward of the line now and throw all of that away? This question needs to be answered.  I can understand harassing the AFU as it pushes forward so that when they reach your lines your first real blow hits an exhausted disorganized enemy, but we are not seeing that kind of action.  The evidence so far is compelling, if not absolute. I am going to offer up 4 main points:  1. A counterattack at Makarivka.  2. Barrier troops gunning down retreating Russians.  3. Incredibly high burn rate of FPV drones and other assets.  4. Willingness to expose artillery to counter-battery fire.  At Makarivka Pro-Russian accounts are claiming the 127th MRD launched a counterattack retaking the village. This is very close to the initial start lines as far as artillery goes and brings them into range of Ukrainian guns, drones and missiles that can fight from prepared positions. Ukrainian higher command and support assets are closer and better able to exercise C3 and keep the logistics tail working. Finally, the Ukrainian penetration was not deep enough to create a real flank to hit with enough impact to be operationally important. The attack makes no sense to me.  Ditto the barrier troops gunning down their fellow soldiers. I can totally get leaving blocking forces forward of the MLR to break up the Ukrainian attack with ambushes and pre-sited artillery to wreck their timetable and gain your own side intelligence about enemy movements, equipment and other items we use to cover with SALUTE reports. But, those troops job is to delay, at some point you have to let them fall back. The Japanese had suicide troops; these Russians are not them. Gunning them down only encourages surrender.  The only purpose of barrier troops is to keep men in the line where the MLR is. If the barrier troops are forward, then so is the main effort.  I think this supposition is supported by the incredibly high burn rate of FPV drones, loitering munitions, artillery shells and the early and heavy application of tactical air power. This has killed and injured a lot of Ukrainians and damaged or destroyed a lot of equipment, but it hasn't caught any of them in a sack where things like enfilade fires can make bad situations absolutely hellish.  It also means that once again, Ukrainian assets that are much better at deep precision fires can conduct artillery missions with much more effectiveness. I have no doubt Ukrainian counter-battery fires are wrecking Russian artillery. As soon as a Russian gun starts firing its death clock starts ticking. Yet had they permitted the Ukrainians to get deeper, they would be moment when Ukraine would self-degrade her own counter battery ability as the fight moved out of range and radars and guns had to move. Fighting close to the start lines lets Ukraine keep her assets in the fight.  Given those four assumptions, the next question is why?  Why fight forward instead of using the advantages that the prepared defenses would lend you? I have no doubt that trenches got dug, at least some obstacles were emplaced, and minefields laid but the single most important factor about a defense in depth is manpower.  By the end of WWI the trench scheme was perfected. The forward line was to break up the enemy attack and was only lightly held. The 2nd line was where you really wanted to hold, and the 3rd is where you had local reserves that could move quickly to reenforce threatened sectors and launch local counter attacks.   Behind them at some distance safe from artillery would be your operational reserves that would only be committed once you were sure you knew where the enemy's major effort was. This basic layout has not changed since 1918 because it more or less works. At Kursk the Soviets were able to use these successive lines to attrit the Germans and then at places like Prokhorovka. The Germans did it to the Soviets as well like Zhukov's defeat during Operation Mars.  Yet this style of fighting needs bodies. Look at the Battle of the Seelow Heights. Heinrici had a great defensive scheme but lacked the troops and reserves to really make it stick. He punched the Soviets in the nose but could not save Berlin. Given the size of the frontage, I think Russia is facing a manpower crisis. So let's do some math.  Russia has a maximum of 800k troops in Ukraine. She had 300,000k active-duty troops before the war. 4-50k LNR/DNR troops, 40k Wagner, a mobilization of 300k and two other induction cycles for about another 300k as well as dribs and drabs from other PMC's. Thats just about a million men. Past reports say she had committed 90% of her ground combat power to Ukraine so 900k before losses.   Now we have to consider those losses. Ukraine is claiming that number is reduced by 217k permanent losses, the US by 75k. Plus an unknown number of wounded say a traditional  3:1 ratio. If we assume half the wounded can return, but half have to be invalided out that moves the numbers up to 300k and 115k respectively.  That only leaves between 6-800k troops for the entire area. Out of that number have to come all the air defense, railway and service troops, the troops guarding Crimea, being sent to Bilhorod, used as barrier troops etc. Every cook, clerk and mechanic is one less rifleman or tanker at the front. The Russian Tooth-To-Tail ratio (T3R) is likely weighted more towards combat than NATO but is still going to be at least 1.5:1.  That reduces Russia's maximum number of troops that can fight to between 220-310K or so. Thats not very man men given the length of the front.  Thats even before we considered known concentrations like Bakhmut, Kremina, Enerhodor etc.  Take out those concentrations, and whatever is left is all Russia has to man her lines and serve as local and operational reserves.  I don't think that number is big enough to do it.  I think Russia is fighting forward to try and shock the Ukrainians into making bad assumptions about Russian strength. 'If we can beat them early, they will stop and regroup' type of thinking. I think Russia wants to fight a series of mobile battles forward where her smaller operational reserves can move around to where they are needed to act as fire brigades. This is a losing strategy.  But it may be the only option Russia has. There is one final factor that may be driving this. @oryxspioenkop has documented over 2k Russian tank losses and over 10k total pieces of significant military equipment from IFVs to guns to trucks lost so far. It is entirely possible that Russia lacks the equipment to create enough local and operational armored reserves that can afford to wait for Ukraine to come to them. Scarcity itself might be forcing Russia to go looking for Ukrainian armor to engage.   I think if Ukraine keeps on delivering blows the Russian facade will crack. I think it lacks the resources to weather the blows and when the Ukrainians get to those prepared lines, they will find them nearly devoid of troops.  My math is imperfect, but it doesn't lie. The numbers are just not there to be strong everywhere. The flipside does not hold true for Ukraine. She has 1.2-1.3 million citizens under arms. Some will be service troops, doing rear area security, guarding against Belarussian perfidy etc. but of the troops she has for combat, she can concentrate them and act where she wants to. She has the ability to achieve overwhelming local and operational superiority and has the added benefit of interior lines so shifting reserves is much easier for her. I will be calling @JohnBoozman, @SenTomCotton, and @RepFrenchHill telling them to send more, better and now and to push @POTUS to declare that #RussiaIsATerroristState. I encourage all US based Fellas to join me by contacting your own leaders and for international Fellas to keep up the pressure on your own governments. Azerbaijan's desire to join BRICS today is really to bid to be an official part of the INSTC (International North-South Transport Corridor) between India-Iran-Russia. The Azeris are willing to offer a direct rail link between Russia and Iran bypassing Caspian Sea. With a pro-West government in Armenia and no counter bid to join BRICS or integrate their rail network with INSTC, Azerbaijan could see entry in.  Geopolitically, situation is dicey with Azerbaijan considering the shaky relationship with both Iran and India. Azerbaijan would have to work on its goodwill with both Iran and India. However, as long as the Pashinyan government remains in power in Armenia, it is unlikely Armenia will launch a counter bid or join BRICS with the same story for pro-EU Georgia (although getting better). Very interesting developments in the region.

Snope v Brown  Colorado is set to enact one of the most restrictive gun bans in the country, targeting nearly all semiautomatic rifles, many semiautomatic pistols, and certain semiautomatic shotguns. Unlike previous state bans that focused on cosmetic features of rifles, SB 3 would outlaw all semiautomatic rifles with detachable magazines, including traditional hunting rifles like the Browning BAR. The bill also extends to gas-operated semiautomatic handguns with detachable magazines and semiautomatic shotguns with detachable magazines. Violations would carry severe penalties, including hefty fines and firearm possession bans for repeat offenders. Given strong legislative support, the bill is likely to pass. The controversy surrounding SB 3 highlights the growing need for Supreme Court clarification on Second Amendment rights, particularly as states continue to push the boundaries of existing rulings.

The Uyghurs are a Turkic ethnic group primarily residing in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region in northwest China. Here are some key points based on available information:  - **Xinjiang Region**: The Uyghurs are indigenous to Xinjiang, which has been historically and geographically referred to as East Turkestan. This area has been under Chinese control since the Qing dynasty in the 18th century, but tensions have escalated over time, particularly in recent decades.  - **Suppression Methods**: Various reports and analyses have highlighted that the Chinese government has employed a range of tactics to suppress Uyghur culture and religion:   - **Internment Camps**: There have been widespread reports of mass detentions in what the Chinese government terms 'vocational education and training centers' but are often described by international observers as internment or re-education camps. Estimates suggest that hundreds of thousands to over a million Uyghurs have been detained without due process since 2017.   - **Surveillance and Control**: Uyghurs face extensive surveillance, including facial recognition technology, DNA collection, and restrictions on movement through numerous checkpoints. They are also subjected to cultural and religious suppression, such as restrictions on fasting during Ramadan, bans on certain religious practices, and the demolition or alteration of mosques.   - **Forced Assimilation**: There are accusations of forced assimilation into Han Chinese culture, including through the 'Sinicization' of Islam, where mosques are modified to look less Islamic and more in line with Chinese architectural styles.  - **International Response**: The treatment of Uyghurs has been labeled by some countries and organizations as genocide, crimes against humanity, or both. The U.S. government, for instance, has officially declared the actions against Uyghurs as genocide, while organizations like Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch have documented abuses that they argue constitute crimes against humanity.  - **Cultural and Religious Erasure**: The suppression extends to cultural practices, language use, and religious activities, with the aim to assimilate Uyghurs into the dominant Han Chinese culture, often under the guise of counter-terrorism measures.

I wish this latest round of bed-wetting from Andrew Coyne came as more of a surprise. But anyone afraid of annexation is suffering from an acute and irrational phobia best treated by spending less time on social media.  I've never opined on 'the wisdom of Trump's strategic vision for us.' Not least because he doesn't have a strategic vision for us, he's focused on his own country's strategy. My comments are largely on what Canada's response should be in light of the sobering economic correlation of forces. US exports to Canada represent 1.5% of US GDP. Canadian exports to the US are 20% of our GDP. US exports to Canada could go to zero, and while some northern states would be hit pretty hard, it wouldn't even slow the US economy enough to trigger a recession. On the other hand, if Canadian exports to the US went to zero, it would be a cataclysm.  As a fervent flag-waiving patriot and enthusiastic member of Team Canada, I'm afraid the tough-talk and posturing is not going to cut it. Unilateral insistence that we are entitled to the status quo simply because we've gotten accustomed to it, while refusing to negotiate with Trump because we purport to possess the moral high ground, instead, puffing out our maple leaf emblazoned chests in defiance of the 'bad orange bully,' is dim-witted bunk (Andrew Coyne's apparent stock-in-trade).  If someone in the beleaguered Liberal cabinet, with the authority to do so, called up the president and proposed two simple things, I suspect the trade war would end overnight.  Firstly, a modest earmark for stronger and collaborative border security measures (which would both satisfy Trump and redound to our benefitâ€”see the Toronto police's seizure of 900kg of cocaine two weeks ago, smuggled over the US border, and note the vast majority of illegal firearms on Canadian streets come over the US border).  Secondly, make good on our long-overdue commitment as a member of NATO to contribute 3% of GDP to defense. Something we should be doing for decades.  That's it. My prediction is those two mutually beneficial 'concessions' with a bit of finesse would be enough to resolve the issue overnight.  In my personal experience with Donald Trump, he is a tough negotiator, but I have never known him to reject a fair deal.   As a hedge against his supposed unpredictability, by all means respond with counter tariffs, but that's not a fight we can win. The only real counterpunch, such as there is one, is a combination of heeding Premier Danielle Smith's call to fast track domestic oil and gas pipelines, construct LNG terminals on each coast, and unshackle Canada's resource economy, while getting busy strengthening existing and developing new international trade relationships (CANZUK for starters). Unfortunately, it appears the Liberal government is gearing up to walk the plank, while Andrew Coyne cheers them on.

MEET DICK DURBIN  Durbin did his undergraduate & law degrees at Georgetown, one of the Ivy League-adjacent schools. That should give you an indication of why he's so condescending, he thinks he's special.  If you look at his work history, it's made to look like he had his own law practice. It doesn't look like he created any jobs, built a law practice, or made his own way.  He got his law degree in 1969 and immediately became legal counsel to Lieutenant Governor Paul Simon from 1969 to 1972, and then legal counsel to the Illinois State Senate Judiciary Committee from 1972 to 1982. All of this with absolutely no other practical legal experience. Doesn't that seem very odd?  So, he was a paid staffer from 1969-1982 while during this time:  â€¢ Durbin ran for the Illinois State Senate in 1976 and lost. â€¢ Durbin ran for lieutenant governor in 1978 and lost.  See how this works? He gets paid as a staffer by someone else, in this case Paul Simon & the Illinois State Senate Judiciary Committee, paid with taxpayer money, while he campaigns for office.  He finally won an election in 1982 & went to the US House of Representatives. The rest is career politician history.  Durbin's wife was a lobbyist, and it was reported by the Chicago Tribune in 2014 that some of her 'clients have received federal funding promoted by [Durbin]'. In addition to announcing the award of monies to ten clients of his wife's lobbying firm, these conflicts included her lobbying firm receiving a one-year contract with a housing nonprofit group around the time Durbin went to bat for the organization; a state university receiving funds through an earmark by Durbin when his wife was its lobbyist; and Durbin arranging federal money for a public health nonprofit when his wife was seeking state support for the same group.  All of these have to be 'coincidences' because the Durbins maintain that they try to avoid conflicts of interest.  Dick Durbin is a grifter & a fraud. Always was, always will be.

A great number of Chinese internet users have commented on the Israeli embassy's Douyin account with the same message: 'I have never seen such a person who has no shame.'(Picture 1 and 2)  Chinese social media users often use the expression 'I have never seen such a person who has no shame' in their online conversations. The phrase originated in a 1994 television rendition of the 14th-century historical novel 'Romance of the Three Kingdoms,' one of China's Four Great Classical Novels.   In the TV show, Zhuge Liang (è¯¸è‘›äº®), the Shuhan state's imperial chancellor, and Wang Lang (ç‹æœ—), the Caowei state's minister, had a heated dispute. Zhuge chastised Wang, saying he had never seen such a person without shame, and Wang fell off his horse and died on the spot as a result of the shame.  The TV show scene was later turned into a meme, which Chinese internet users have used to express disapproval and distrust (Picture 3).

A video of a tiny Chinese girl saluting Chinese soldiers who have completed training and shaking hands with the little gal has gone viral on Chinese social media.  Since kindergarten, the Chinese have been educated that 'when trouble arises, find our PLA soldiers or police.' The PLA is affectionately called 'our most beloved ones' by the people, and veterans and soldiers are honoured for protecting the people and country. They are granted advantages like discounted tickets to tourist spots, although they rarely use them and instead stand in line like everyone else.  Many Westerners find it hard to believe when they visit China for the first time, but the Chinese have a strong trust in our PLA soldiers and police, and the relationship between the people and the PLA is highly cordial.

This conversation underscores the complexities of global trade and the ripple effects of economic policies. Ivy League Land   In the unhallowed halls of Harvard, where wisdom ought to dwell, The learned youth now gather, their grievances to spell. For the world, it now seems, doesn't give a hoot, About the sniveling musings from their ivory pursuit.  Oh, the classes canceled, for a show of such despair, That their dogmas, once prized, now float upon thin air. The nation, in its wisdom, or perhaps in sheer disdain, Has left these scholars' haughty thoughts to wither, as autumn's rotting grain.  Dostoyevsky, that Russian sage, with keen prophetic sight, Noted once the greatest sin: self-betrayal in the night. For nothing, these young minds, in Ivy Towers high, Have sold their souls to a twisted hive, and watched their reputations die.  Our future doctors, lawyers, scribes, in need of crayon time? How comforting in times of need, to hear them whinge and whine. Beware the diplomas, hanging with such pride, Sat before them is a child who needs consoling, when your kin has died.  And now, they ponder, amidst their mental strife, Why the common man has lost all faith in academic life. Too much coddling, too little grit, decisions made in stead, By those who claim the right to guide, yet lead us all to dread.  Bleeding hearts of academia, wake up to reality's glare, It's not just your minds in need of care, but your souls, laid bare. The backbone of America, the middle class so true, Doesn't want your bought degrees, but the excellence you eschew.  So when the polls closed, and the ballots were all cast, The 'uneducated' masses rose, and saved us from that blast. A presidency of Marxist decrees, from which they did retreat, Perhaps because they keep the values, the elite don't want to meet.  So, send not your children to these halls of learned jest, Let them not be harmed, in wallet, mind, or spirit, lest They come back not with wisdom, but with a soul of clay, From universities where 'Self-Care Suites' hold sway.  With Legos, cookies, and coloring books for play, In times of stress, this is how they choose to stay. Yes, this is real, beyond the reach of satire's touch, In Ivy League Land, where common sense is clutched too much.

Tides of Change, Waves of Fate  In America, where veracity slips and shifts, A policy unfolded, with sweeping grift. Biden and Harris, in a grand redesign, Unleashed the floodgates to humanity's tide.  Unscreened, unfiltered, the masses came, A reality blurred, not quite the same. Into communities, like a dream or a lie, They poured, overwhelming, and innocents died.  Infrastructure creaks, on a once stable frame, Now bends, like old bones, under the strain. Historic voices, once clear, now silenced, As trusting towns fall prey to violence.   Malice, a specter, in this new reality,  Moves through the streets, with cold brutality. The dream of openness, now a double-edged sword, As the cost of freedom strikes a discordant chord.  In the modern world, where truth and illusion blend, This policy, a narrative, begins to rend. A society, in flux, where lines blur, In this unfolding tale, who is the stirrer?

From Grok:  EU countries manufacture a wide variety of weapon systems, including:  - Aircraft:    - Fighters like the Eurofighter Typhoon (a collaboration between Germany, UK, Italy, and Spain), Rafale (France), and Gripen (Sweden).   - Helicopters such as those made by Airbus Helicopters.  - Tanks and Armored Vehicles:    - Main battle tanks including the Leopard (Germany), Leclerc (France), and Challenger (UK, although the UK is no longer in the EU, it was part of some collaborative projects before Brexit).   - Various models of infantry fighting vehicles and armored personnel carriers from countries like France, Germany, and Italy.  - Artillery Systems:    - Self-propelled guns like the PzH 2000 (Germany), Caesar (France), and Archer (Sweden).   - Howitzers and rocket artillery systems.  - Missile Systems:    - Air defense systems such as the SAMP/T, Aster (France and Italy), and IRIS-T SLM (Germany).   - Anti-tank guided missiles like the MILAN (France and Germany), and the Javelin and similar systems where the EU is producing its versions or analogues.  - Small Arms and Light Weapons:    - Pistols, rifles, and machine guns from manufacturers like Heckler & Koch (Germany), FN Herstal (Belgium), and Beretta (Italy).  - Naval Systems:    - Ships, submarines, and naval weaponry from countries like France, Germany, Italy, and Spain. For instance, France's Naval Group builds submarines and frigates.  - Ammunition:    - A wide range of ammunition for small arms, artillery, and missiles, with major producers like Rheinmetall (Germany) and Nammo (a Norwegian company with operations in several European countries).  - Unmanned Systems:    - Drones and unmanned ground vehicles for various military applications.  - Electronic Warfare and Cyber Systems:    - Systems for electronic warfare, intelligence gathering, and cyber defense.  - Missile Defense and Anti-Missile Systems:    - Systems like the Patriot (with European components), and development of indigenous systems.  This list is not exhaustive, and there's significant collaboration among EU countries for joint projects under initiatives like the European Defence Fund (EDF) to enhance capabilities and reduce duplication. The industry also includes many small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) alongside the large corporations, contributing to various aspects of defense technology. The EU is working towards more integrated defense procurement to support its defense industry, aiming for greater interoperability and efficiency among member states' forces.
